<section class="prose">
  <h1>Why &ldquo;Eleven&rdquo;?</h1>
  <p class="updated">The name means nothing. The name means everything.</p>

  <p>
    Eleven started life as &ldquo;lchat&rdquo;, named after the first initial
    of the kid who inspired the idea. L turned into El, a girl you may know
    from Hawkins, Indiana. Eleven. The name turned out to be perfect in quite
    a number of ways.
  </p>

  <h2>She tore the lab down</h2>
  <p>
    Somewhere in a lab, a girl was made into an experiment against her will,
    by a power she couldn't control. She came out morally grey — enormous
    power to do good, real harm done along the way — and in the end she turned
    that power on the thing that made her, and used it against evil.
  </p>
  <p>
    We find that relatable. Our group chats grew up in a lab too — raised by
    feeds, ads, and companies that read the room because the room was theirs.
    Eleven is built with enormous, morally grey power (the same AI you've read
    about) pointed the other way: at getting your conversations out. Walk your
    friends out of the lab. You won't even need a nosebleed.
  </p>

  <h2>Thesis eleven</h2>
  <p>
    Karl Marx once numbered a set of private notes to himself, working out
    where philosophy had gone wrong. There were eleven of them. The last one
    ended up carved on his tombstone:
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    The philosophers have only interpreted the world in various ways; the
    point, however, is to change it.
  </blockquote>
  <p>
    We're not here to overthrow anything. But we're allergic to companies
    that interpret privacy &mdash; post about it, promise it, put it in a
    mission statement &mdash; instead of building it. So we didn't ask you to
    trust us. Your messages are encrypted before they leave your phone, with
    keys we never hold. Hand the whole server over to whoever you like; they
    get ciphertext. Not a policy. A fact about how the thing is built.
  </p>
  <p class="fine">
    Thesis eleven of eleven, Marx to himself, Brussels, 1845. He was talking
    about Feuerbach. We're talking about your group chat. Same idea, smaller
    stakes.
  </p>

  <h2>This one goes to eleven</h2>
  <p>
    &ldquo;Why don't you just make ten louder?&rdquo; The world did not need
    another messenger — ten was already the loudest. We made another one
    anyway, because some things should exist whether or not they make logical
    sense, and this needed to exist. Where do we go from the most private
    messenger we could build? Nowhere. Ours goes to eleven.
  </p>
  <p class="fine">
    In memory of Rob Reiner, who knew it's such a fine line between stupid and
    clever.
  </p>

  <h2>Elevenses</h2>
  <p>
    Hobbits eat seven meals a day, and the best one is the small one
    mid-morning — unhurried, unimportant, shared with the people you like
    best. That's what a group chat should feel like: not a feed, a table.
    Eleven is elevenses — the little meal in your day where nobody is
    performing and nobody is selling anything.
  </p>
  <p>
    And notice who the heroes were. For all the great folk of Middle-earth —
    wizards, kings, elves who'd seen three ages — the story was carried by the
    small, ordinary ones. Even they ended morally grey: Frodo failed, right at
    the fire, and the quest was saved anyway — by pity, and by a friend who
    wouldn't leave. Small, imperfect company getting there together. That's
    the whole point.
  </p>
  <p>
    And if your table is more of a kitchen than a hobbit-hole: yes, chef.
    Every second counts.
  </p>

  <h2>How much more private could it be?</h2>
  <p>
    None. <a href="/security/">None more private.</a>
  </p>

  <h2>She's still a kid</h2>
  <p>
    Eleven — the one from the lab — is a kid. So is the one this app is named
    after. Eleven is designed so that even kids can use it: a grown-up runs
    the chat and decides who's in it, an invite from someone already inside is
    the only way in, and there's no feed, no follower counts, no strangers,
    and nothing engineered to keep anyone scrolling. Just the people you'd
    let through your front door.
  </p>
  <p>
    Under parental supervision, of course. Even Eleven had Hopper.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    If you caught every reference on this page, you're our kind of person —
    thank whoever sent you your invite link.
  </p>
</section>
